            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1. He was 18, his father\u2019s calloused hands guiding his own, tying the precise knot on a new prosciutto. The deli air, rich with the perfume of provolone, felt like a cage. He loved his father, but in that moment, he saw his future hanging before him\u2014a life he respected but didn\u2019t want. It wasn\u2019t rebellion that pushed him away, but the quiet, heartbreaking realization that he had to break his father\u2019s heart to follow his own. That guilt became the foundation of his drive.\n\n2. He remembers the darkness of the lecture hall at SF State, around age 20. A slide of a Bernini sculpture illuminated the screen, freezing a story in marble. The professor spoke of form and tension, but Marco felt an almost spiritual connection, a sense of belonging that had nothing to do with family or obligation. It was the first time he understood that beauty could be its own justification. That single image became his North Star, a private validation for choosing a different path.\n\n3. He was 28, presenting a meticulously crafted mood board for a new window display. The VP of finance glanced at it, then at a spreadsheet, and said, \u201cThe numbers don\u2019t support this.\u201d The dismissal was swift, clinical. Marco felt a hot flush of humiliation followed by a cold wave of clarity. Creativity wasn\u2019t enough; power spoke a different language. That evening, he started researching MBA programs. His ambition was no longer just about art; it was about gaining control.\n\n4. The silence after she left was the loudest thing he\u2019d ever heard. He was 32, sitting at his dining table, the apartment suddenly vast. His open MBA textbook felt like the very reason for the emptiness. He had chosen this grueling path, the relentless push forward, but never fully calculated the personal cost. In that quiet, he first felt the specific loneliness that would become his companion\u2014the shadow cast by his own success. It was the price he paid for the life he was building.\n\n5. Just last month, standing alone in his kitchen after a dinner party, the air still held the ghost of laughter. He\u2019d orchestrated a perfect evening, a performance of the warmth he missed from his childhood. But as he rinsed the wine glasses, he felt a familiar, hollow ache. He had become an expert at building the scenery for a happy life, a beautiful stage filled with friends and good food. The realization hit him hard: he was still waiting for someone to share it with."
